## AuthorText1('Anton')
## EditionText1('9')
## Section1('4.4')
## Problem1('12')
## KEYWORDS('Absolute Maximum', 'Absolute Minimum', 'Extreme Value Theorem')
#***************************************************************
#   Initialization - Load standard PG and MathObjects macros
#***************************************************************

## Updated 2025.02 by Peter Staab, switch to PGML

DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
    'PGstandard.pl',      'PGML.pl',
    'PGunion.pl',         'littleneck.pl',
    'contextFraction.pl', 'PGcourse.pl'
);

# Setup
Context('Numeric');

$sign = random(-1, 1, 2);
$PM   = random(-1, 1, 2);

$f  = Formula("$PM*(x^2 +$sign*x)^(2/3)")->reduce;
$fp = Formula("$PM*2(2x +$sign)/(3(x^2+$sign*x))^(1/3)")->reduce;

if ($sign > 0) {
    $signdisp = '+';
    $a1       = random(2, 3, 1);
    $a        = -$a1;
    $b        = $a1 + 1;
    $fa       = $a1 * ($a1 - 1);
    $fb       = ($a1 + 1) * ($a1 + 2);
    $cp1      = -1;
    $cp2      = 0;
    Context("Fraction");
    $sp  = Compute("-1/2");
    $fsp = Compute("-1/4");
    Context("Numeric");

    if ($PM > 0) {
        $disp  = '';
        $Max   = "$fb^\frac{2}{3}";
        $Min   = 0;
        $ans_a = Compute("$fb^(2/3)");
        $ans_b = List("$b");
        $ans_c = Compute("0");
        $ans_d = List("$cp1, $cp2");

    } else {
        $disp  = '-';
        $Min   = "-$fb^\frac{2}{3}";
        $Max   = 0;
        $ans_c = Compute("-$fb^(2/3)");
        $ans_d = List("$b");
        $ans_a = Compute("0");
        $ans_b = List("$cp1, $cp2");
    }

} else {
    $signdisp = '-';
    $a1       = random(3, 4, 1);
    $a        = -$a1;
    $b        = $a1 - 1;
    $fa       = $a1 * ($a1 + 1);
    $fb       = ($a1 - 1) * ($a1 - 2);
    $cp1      = 0;
    $cp2      = 1;
    Context("Fraction");
    $sp  = Compute("1/2");
    $fsp = Compute("-1/4");
    Context("Numeric");

    if ($PM > 0) {
        $disp  = '';
        $Max   = "$fa^\frac{2}{3}";
        $Min   = 0;
        $ans_a = Compute("$fa^(2/3)");
        $ans_b = List("$a");
        $ans_c = Compute("0");
        $ans_d = List("$cp1, $cp2");

    } else {
        $disp  = '-';
        $Min   = "-($fa)^\frac{2}{3}";
        $Max   = 0;
        $ans_c = Compute("-$fa^(2/3)");
        $ans_d = List("$a");
        $ans_a = Compute("0");
        $ans_b = List("$cp1, $cp2");
    }
}

# Main text

BEGIN_PGML
Find the absolute maximum and minimum values of [`f(x) = [$disp](x^2 [$signdisp] x)^\frac{2}{3}`] over the interval [`[ [$a], [$b] ]`].

- There is an absolute maximum is [_]{$ans_b}{15} and it occurs at x = [_]{$ans_a}{15} 
- There is an absolute minimum is [_]{$ans_d}{15} and it occurs at x = [_]{$ans_c}{15}

*Notes:* If there is more than one [`x`] value, enter as a comma separated list.

END_PGML



BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The function [`f`] is continuous everywhere and therefore the Extreme-Value Theorem guarantees that [`f`] has a maximum and a minimum value
 on the interval [`[ [$a], [$b] ]`].

 Differentiating, we obtain

[``` f'(x) = [$disp] \frac{2(2x [$signdisp] 1)}{3(x^2 [$signdisp] x)^\frac{1}{3}}```]

Thus [`f'(x) =0`] if [`x =[$sp] `] and [` f'(x)`] is undefined if [` x =[$cp1]`] or [` x= [$cp2]`].
Evaluating [`f`] at these critical values and end points yields the following table

[#
    [.[`x`].] [.[`f(x)`].]*
    [.[`[$a]`].] [.[`[$disp][$fa]^{2/3}`].]*
    [.[`[$cp1]`].] [.[`0`].]* 
    [.[`[$sp]`].]  [.[`[$disp] ([$fsp])^{2/3}`].]*
    [.[`[$cp2]`].] [.[`0`].]*
    [.[`[$b]`].] [. [`[$disp] ([$fb])^{2/3} `] .]*
#]{horizontalrules => 1, padding => [0.5, 0.5], align => '|c|c|'}

We conclude that [`f`] has an absolute maximum of [`[$Max]`]which occurs at [` x = [$ans_b]`] and [`f`] has an absolute minimum of [`[$Min] `] which occurs at [`x =[$ans_d]`].
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
